libx11: fix LTO -Werror diagnostics (array-bounds / stringop-overflow /
        maybe-uninitialized) and two latent correctness bugs they exposed.

Builds under the clang/GCC "llvm-ultimate"-style aggressive LTO configuration
abort in several translation units. This patch resolves every diagnostic at the
source and, in doing so, fixes two genuine bugs (not mere warning suppression):

1) src/xlibi18n/XDefaultOMIF.c  (_XmbDefaultTextExtents)
   -Wmaybe-uninitialized on overall.*: XTextExtents() always fully initialises
   'overall' (glyph loop, or its nfound==0 zeroing branch); LTO just cannot see
   through the call. Zero-initialise the aggregate; the store is elided when the
   optimiser can prove it dead.

2) src/XlibInt.c  (_XGetHostname, inlined into XSetWMProperties)
   -Werror=array-bounds: clamp the copy length to sizeof(name.nodename) BEFORE
   the maxlen clamp so the source read is provably within nodename[65], and use
   memcpy() for the exact length. Behaviour unchanged for valid hostnames.

3) modules/im/ximcp/imDefIm.c  (_XimProtoSetIMValues, XIM_OVERFLOW path)
   -Wmaybe-uninitialized on preply exposed a REAL bug: the oversized reply was
   re-read into the fixed BUFSIZE stack buffer 'reply' instead of the freshly
   Xmalloc()'d 'preply' (len > BUFSIZE by definition), overflowing the stack and
   leaving 'preply' uninitialised before dereference. Read into 'preply' and
   guard the allocation, exactly as the sibling _XimProtoGetIMValues() does.

4) src/GetHints.c  (XGetClassHint)
   -Werror=array-bounds / -Werror=stringop-overflow: strcpy() into buffers just
   sized with Xmalloc(len+1). Under LTO the pass cannot prove strcpy()'s implicit
   strlen() equals the computed len and reports an out-of-bounds write into the
   malloc'd region. Replace both copies with bounded memcpy(len+1) (NUL included)
   — provably in-range and semantically identical.

Signed-off-by: ms178
--- a/src/xlibi18n/XDefaultOMIF.c	2026-07-19 14:44:25.386448717 +0000
+++ b/src/xlibi18n/XDefaultOMIF.c	2026-07-19 14:44:25.482448717 +0000
@@ -632,7 +632,12 @@
 		       XRectangle *overall_ink, XRectangle *overall_logical)
 {
     int direction, logical_ascent, logical_descent;
-    XCharStruct overall;
+    /* Zero-initialised: XTextExtents() always fully populates 'overall' (either
+     * from the glyph loop or via its nfound==0 zeroing branch), but with LTO the
+     * compiler cannot see across the call and emits a -Wmaybe-uninitialized false
+     * positive.  A definite initialiser makes the intent explicit and is elided
+     * by the optimiser whenever it can prove the store is redundant. */
+    XCharStruct overall = { 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0 };
 
     XTextExtents(*oc->core.font_info.font_struct_list, text, length, &direction,
 		 &logical_ascent, &logical_descent, &overall);
--- a/src/XlibInt.c	2026-07-19 14:44:25.394448717 +0000
+++ b/src/XlibInt.c	2026-07-19 14:44:25.482448717 +0000
@@ -1723,8 +1723,16 @@
 
     uname (&name);
     len = (int) strlen (name.nodename);
+    /* Clamp to the ACTUAL size of the source field first.  uname() null-
+     * terminates nodename, so strlen() is safe, but under LTO the array-bounds
+     * pass inlines the caller's maxlen (e.g. 256 from XSetWMProperties) and
+     * cannot prove strlen()'s result fits in nodename[_UTSNAME_NODENAME_LENGTH]
+     * (65), reporting a spurious (but formally correct) -Werror=array-bounds.
+     * Bounding by sizeof(name.nodename) makes the read provably in-range. */
+    if (len >= (int) sizeof (name.nodename))
+	len = (int) sizeof (name.nodename) - 1;
     if (len >= maxlen) len = maxlen - 1;
-    strncpy (buf, name.nodename, (size_t) len);
+    memcpy (buf, name.nodename, (size_t) len);
     buf[len] = '\0';
 #else
     if (maxlen <= 0 || buf == NULL)
